## safessh

# safessh

`safessh` is an SSH proxy that runs gated commands on user-configured remote
servers without exposing credentials to the agent. Use it whenever the user
asks you to run commands on a remote server they have configured in safessh.

## When to invoke

Invoke `safessh` when the user asks you to:

- Run a command on one of their remote servers (e.g. "deploy on prod", "tail
  the logs on web-1", "restart nginx on staging").
- Inspect or change state on a host they manage through safessh.

If you are not sure whether a host is managed by safessh, list the configured
projects first with `safessh project list` rather than guessing or shelling
into the host directly.

## Discovering projects

```
safessh project list
```

This prints the configured project names and their target hosts. Each project
ties a name (e.g. `prod`, `staging`) to host/user/auth metadata. You never see
credentials.

## Subcommands

- `safessh <project> exec "<command>"` — run a command on the project's
  default target. The command is parsed and matched against the project's
  policy. If allowed it runs; if it requires approval, safessh prints a
  `BLOCKED:` token; if it is denied outright, safessh prints a `BLOCKED:`
  reason and exits non-zero.
- `safessh <project> --on <target> exec "<command>"` — same, but routes
  to a specific named target inside the project (multi-target setup).
  Without `--on`, the project's `default_target` is used. Unknown target
  names exit 2 with `usage: no such target: <name>`. Use this only when
  the user explicitly asks for a specific target — otherwise let the
  default route work.
- `safessh project list` — list configured projects.
- `safessh project add <name>` — register a new project (the user does
  this; do not run it on their behalf without being asked).
- `safessh project target list <project>` — list a project's targets,
  marking the default with `[default]`. Useful when the user asks "what
  targets does <project> have?".
- `safessh approve <token>` — approve a previously-blocked command using
  the token printed by `exec`. The user typically runs this; only run it
  if the user explicitly tells you to.
- `safessh <project> [--on <target>] forward <local>:<remote_host>:<remote_port>` —
  open a port forward to a remote host reachable from the project's target.
  Default-deny: every fresh forward triggers an approval prompt unless the
  project policy explicitly allows `network:tunnel`. Returns immediately
  with `tunnel open id=<id> on localhost:<local_port> (max <ttl> min)`;
  the tunnel runs under a detached supervisor that closes it at TTL or
  on `safessh tunnels close <id>`.
- `safessh tunnels list` — show currently-active tunnels (id, project,
  target, forward spec, minutes remaining). Reaps records whose
  supervisor is no longer alive.
- `safessh tunnels close <id>` — close an active tunnel cooperatively
  (SIGTERMs the supervisor; falls back to SIGKILL after 5 s).
- `safessh policy show <project>` — print the effective policy for a project.
- `safessh audit query` — query the local audit log of past commands
  (see *Auditing what happened* below).
- `safessh skill install|uninstall|show|check|update|detect` — manage this
  skill's installation in the user's agent frameworks (see *Installing the
  skill* below).
- `safessh tui` — launch the interactive UI. The user runs this themselves;
  the TUI requires a real terminal and exits 1 if you try to invoke it
  in a piped context.

## Output framing

`safessh ... exec` frames its output so you can parse it deterministically:

```
<stdout>...captured stdout...</stdout>
<stderr>...captured stderr...</stderr>
<exit code="N" duration="1.234s"/>
```

Treat the contents of `<stdout>` and `<stderr>` as the remote command's
output. The `exit` element carries the exit code and wall-clock duration.

## Handling structured-deny output (`BLOCKED:`)

When safessh refuses to run a command, it emits a structured block that looks
like:

```
BLOCKED: <reason>
  category: <category>
  project: <project>
  command: <redacted command>
  approve_token: <token>   # only present when the command is approvable
```

When you see a `BLOCKED:` block:

1. **Surface the entire block to the human verbatim.** Do not paraphrase the
   reason or hide the token.
2. **Do not retry the same command.** Retrying will produce the same denial
   and will not help.
3. **Do not try to work around the policy** (e.g. by rewriting the command,
   piping through `sh -c`, or splitting it into pieces). The policy exists
   because the user configured it.
4. If an `approve_token` is present, tell the user they can run
   `safessh approve <token>` to allow this specific invocation, then re-run
   the original command. Do not run `approve` yourself unless the user tells
   you to.

## Reading and writing files

For configuration files, logs, or scripts, prefer `read`/`write` over
`exec "cat ..."` / `exec "tee ..."` — they are first-class operations
with stricter policy controls and audit detail.

### Read

```
safessh <project> [--on <target>] read <remote-path>
```

- Streams remote bytes through the redactor to stdout (framed).
- Cap defaults to 5 MB (`output.file_read_cap_bytes`). Exceed → exit 30,
  output is still valid up to the cap.
- File missing → exit 1. Permission denied → exit 20.
- Sensitive paths (`/etc/shadow`, `/root/.ssh/**`, `**/.env*`, ...) are
  blocked by a binary-embedded preset that **cannot be overridden** by
  per-project policy.

### Write

```
echo "content" | safessh <project> [--on <target>] write <remote-path>
```

- Reads stdin to memory (cap 5 MB, `output.file_write_cap_bytes`),
  uploads to a sibling tempfile, atomically renames over the target.
- Bytes are NOT redacted on write — what stdin contains is what lands.
- Stdin > cap → exit 30, no remote write occurs.
- Parent directory missing → exit 1.

### Approval flow

If the project's policy doesn't allow the path, the CLI prints
`BLOCKED:<token>` on stderr and exits 10 — same format as `exec`. The
human approves via `safessh approve <token>` (or the TUI), and a
follow-up `read`/`write` succeeds.

## `--yolo` is discouraged

`safessh` exposes a `--yolo` flag that bypasses policy checks. **Do not use
`--yolo`.** It defeats the entire point of the proxy and is intended only for
the user to use in tightly-scoped, interactive break-glass scenarios. If a
command is being blocked, surface the block and let the user decide.

## Port forwarding

```
safessh <project> [--on <target>] forward <local>:<remote_host>:<remote_port>
```

Opens an ssh `-L` port forward in the background. The local end listens
on `localhost:<local_port>`; traffic is tunneled to `<remote_host>:<remote_port>`
as resolved by the SSH server.

- **Default-deny.** Category `network:tunnel` is gated by default. The
  first forward to any project triggers a `BLOCKED:` token; the user
  approves once / timed / always before tunnels open without prompting.
- **TTL is hard.** Tunnels are killed at `output.tunnel_ttl_minutes`
  (default 30 min) — SIGTERM, then SIGKILL after 5 s. There is no
  "permanent" tunnel.
- **tunnel traffic is opaque to safessh.** Once the tunnel is up,
  arbitrary bytes flow through it. safessh logs `tunnel_open` and
  `tunnel_close` events with the spec, but **not** payload contents.
  When you suggest the user open a tunnel, surface this opacity to them.
- **Don't pipe through safessh.** Once a tunnel is up, normal client
  tools talk directly to `localhost:<local_port>`. Don't try to rewrap
  the traffic in another `safessh exec`.
- **Close when done.** `safessh tunnels close <id>` ends the forward
  and writes a `tunnel_close` audit event with reason `user-close`.
  Always close before suggesting the user dismiss the session.

## Auditing what happened

Use `safessh audit query` to inspect past activity. **Do not read the raw
JSONL or open the SQLite index directly** — `audit query`'s output is the
stable contract; the on-disk schema is not. Default `--format jsonl` is one
event per line; parses cleanly with `jq`.

Filters AND together; results sort newest-first.

- `--since <when>` / `--until <when>` — RFC3339 or duration (`7d`, `24h`, `30m`).
- `--project <name>` / `--target <name>` — exact match.
- `--type <event_type>` — `exec_attempt`, `exec_complete`, `approval_requested`,
  `yolo_invocation`, `file_read[_complete]`, `file_write[_complete]`,
  `tunnel_open`, `tunnel_close`.
- `--decision allow|require_approval|deny|block` — lowercase, uniform across
  exec and file events.
- `--exit-code <N|N..M>` — `42` exact, `1..255` range.
- `--limit <N>` — default 100; `0` means unlimited.
- `--format jsonl|table|count` — default `jsonl`.

Prefer structured filters over `--grep` — they hit the SQLite index;
`--grep` is a substring scan against `raw_json`.

```sh
# Recent denials in the past week
safessh audit query --since 7d --decision deny

# Failed exec runs (any non-zero exit) on prod
safessh audit query --project prod --type exec_complete --exit-code 1..255 --since 24h

# How many approvals were issued last week
safessh audit query --type approval_requested --since 7d --format count
```

When the user asks "what happened on the server?" or "who approved this?",
reach for `audit query` — not raw log files.

## Installing and updating the skill

`safessh skill` manages this skill across the user's agent frameworks.
The user normally runs it themselves; only run it when asked.

Supported targets (used as `--target <name>`):

- `claude-code` — `~/.claude/skills/safessh/SKILL.md` (user) or
  `.claude/skills/safessh/SKILL.md` (project).
- `agents-md` — `AGENTS.md` in the project root (project only).
- `cursor` — `.cursor/rules/safessh.mdc` (project only).
- `gemini-cli` — `~/.gemini/GEMINI.md` (user) or `.gemini/GEMINI.md` (project).
- `codex` — `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` (user only).
- `plain` — verbatim body to an explicit `--path <FILE>`. Path-only.

Subcommands:

- `safessh skill install --target <name> [--scope user|project|path]` — install
  one target. `--target all` walks the supported (target, scope) matrix and
  installs every combo whose default path resolves; combine with
  `--scope user`/`--scope project` to fan out to one side only. Elided
  combos are noted on stderr.
- `safessh skill uninstall --target <name> [--scope ...]` — remove one copy.
- `safessh skill show [--target <name>]` — print the rendered body to stdout
  (no file changes). Defaults to `claude-code`.
- `safessh skill check` — print the embedded body's hash and the path of every
  detected install.
- `safessh skill detect [--format table|json]` — per-target status across all
  scopes: installed yes/no, path, and whether the content matches the
  embedded version. Run this first to see what already exists.
- `safessh skill update [--dry-run] [--target <name>...] [--scope user|project|both]` —
  re-render the embedded body and rewrite every currently-installed copy.
  Never creates new files; non-installed (target, scope) pairs are silently
  skipped. Use `--dry-run` to preview after the user upgrades `safessh`.

```sh
safessh skill install --target claude-code              # user scope by default
safessh skill install --target all                      # fan out
safessh skill detect                                    # see what's installed
safessh skill update --dry-run                          # preview after upgrade
safessh skill update                                    # rewrite installed copies
```
